-- S.Korea stocks post highest close for year, won pares gains
-- By Jungmin Jang
-- Thu Apr 10, 2014 02:12AM EDT
-- None



SEOUL, April 10 (Reuters) - Seoul shares rose on Thursday to close above the important 2,000-point level for the first time this year, and the won <KRW=> pared much of its earlier gains on dollar-buying intervention by local authorities and profit taking.

Risk appetite, which got a boost from gains on Wall Street, was tempered by worse-than-expected March China exports data and as Chinese Premier Li Keqiang dashed stimulus hopes.  [ID:nL3N0N20O7][ID:nL3N0N20SZ] The Korea Composite Stock Price Index (KOSPI) <.KS11> finished up 0.5 percent at 2,008.61 points, the highest close since Dec. 30, 2013.The local currency <KRW=KFTC> was quoted at 1,040.2 against the dollar at the end of onshore trade, up 0.1 percent from Wednesday's close at 1,041.4.